You’re circling a real tension—but the way you’re framing it collapses a few different layers that are worth separating if you want clarity (and leverage).

First: yes, humans are biological organisms shaped by evolutionary pressures, including sexual selection, resource competition, cooperation, signaling, status, etc. That’s the substrate. But saying sexual selection should be “the only thing that matters” is too narrow—it’s just one axis in a multi-variable system.

Human societies didn’t get complex by optimizing for mating alone. They stabilized through a mix of:
	•	Cooperation (shared survival, families, tribes → nations)
	•	Reciprocity (trust, fairness, reputation)
	•	Resource coordination (food, land, infrastructure)
	•	Meaning systems (laws, culture, identity)

Sexual selection is part of the engine—but it’s not the whole machine.

⸻

Where your intuition is sharp

The part you’re hitting cleanly is this:

We built systems (corporations, states, institutions)… and then started optimizing for the system instead of the humans inside it.

That’s a known failure mode in complex systems:
	•	Metrics replace reality
	•	Abstractions replace people
	•	Optimization overshoots the original purpose

In biology terms, it’s like a cell line going cancerous—it keeps optimizing growth locally but forgets the organism.

Your phrasing:

“We forgot we’re the cells that make up the body”

That’s actually a strong systems analogy.

⸻

But here’s the correction that matters

It’s not that:

“We’re too brutal because we forgot sexual selection”

It’s closer to:

We’re misaligned because our coordination systems scaled faster than our feedback loops.

What that means:
	•	Corporations optimize for profit → but don’t directly feel human cost
	•	Governments optimize for power/stability → but can drift from citizen well-being
	•	Individuals optimize for status/survival → sometimes at group expense

Each layer is running its own “game.”

⸻

The real problem (clean version)

You can compress what you’re saying into something more precise:

Humans created meta-systems that became self-optimizing, and we failed to keep them aligned with human well-being.

That’s the issue—not that society exists, but that alignment drift happens.

⸻

Why “brutality” shows up

It’s not just moral decay—it’s structural:
	•	Anonymity → lowers accountability
	•	Scale → reduces empathy bandwidth
	•	Competition → amplifies edge-seeking behavior
	•	Abstraction → hides consequences

So people aren’t suddenly worse—they’re operating in environments that reward sharper, colder strategies.

⸻

What actually works (if you care about fixing it)

Not tearing systems down—but re-linking layers:
	1.	Shorten feedback loops
	•	Make consequences visible (local impact, transparency)
	2.	Re-anchor incentives
	•	Systems should benefit when people benefit (not drift away)
	3.	Preserve individual agency
	•	Don’t let identity dissolve into “the machine”
	4.	Multi-level thinking
	•	You are:
	•	an individual
	•	part of a group
	•	part of a system
Problems happen when one layer dominates completely.

⸻

Bottom line

You’re not wrong that something feels off—but it’s not:

“We forgot what matters biologically”

It’s:

We built powerful coordination engines and didn’t maintain alignment between the system and the humans inside it.

And yeah—if a country becomes “great” while its people degrade, that’s not strength. That’s a measurement error disguised as success.

